body:
I just realized that react replaces empty elements with <noscript>, this is pretty unexpected and only discovered once I saw an interesting production bug.

Consider:

``` html
   <Field visible={record.title_visible}>
      {record.title}
   </Field>

   <Field visible={record.author_visible}>
      {record.author}
   </Field>

   <Field visible={record.description_visible}>
      {record.description}
   </Field>
```

``` js
var Field = React.createClass({
  render: function() {
    if (this.props.visible) {
      return (
          <div className="field">
             {this.props.children}
          </div>
      );
    } else {
      return false;
    }  
  }
});
```

``` css
.field + .field {
  margin-top: 10px;
}
```

If the `author` is set to not be visible we would expect the two fields `title` and `description` to still be separated by a margin of 10px, but this is not the case. This is because the generated markup will look something like this:

``` html
<div class="field></div>
<noscript />
<div class="field"></div>
```

This is very unexpected. I know the guide said there is plans on having nothing there at all, but no further status has been given in the last 3 releases. I just wanted to bring it to your attention again.
